                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d897">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 EW/11–244: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-25T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >November 25, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9920. For Pell. Reference your despatch dated November 2 (Embassy’s no. 18981)
                    referring to this Government question whether acts committed for purpose of
                    preparing and launching war can be considered war crimes and within scope of
                    Commission’s work.</p>
                <p>Since despatch not received until November 14, it is impossible to send you
                    instructions in time for Commission’s meeting on November 29. Further time will
                    be necessary to give question careful and adequate consideration. You are
                    accordingly requested to state to Commission that this Government is not now
                    prepared to express an opinion on the matter, and that you therefore are not
                    prepared to vote on the question at this time. Further instructions will be sent
                    as soon as possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
